> Eggplant, mozzarella, and tomato sauce are a true trifecta of Italian cuisine. The mere
> mention of the combo is enough to make anyone weak in the knees. So tossing it with strands
> of al dente linguine seemed like a no-brainer to us, especially with the addition of
> sun-dried tomato to the sauce, which add bursts of tangy flavor throughout.

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Bring a large #pot of salted water
to a boil. Cut @eggplant{1} into ½-inch cubes. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a large
drizzle of @olive oil{} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast in oven until soft and
golden, about ~{20%minutes}, tossing halfway through.

Halve, peel, and finely chop @yellow onion{1}(finely chopped). Thinly slice
@sun-dried tomatoes{1.5%ounce}(thinly sliced). Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}(minced).
Roughly chop @parsley{1/4%ounce}(roughly chopped). Tear @fresh mozzarella{4%ounce} into
small pieces.

Once water is boiling, add @linguine{6%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until
al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Carefully scoop out and reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water,
then drain.

While pasta cooks, heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large pan over medium heat. Add
onion, sun-dried tomatoes, garlic, and a pinch of @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} (to taste).
Cook, tossing, until onions are very soft, ~{5-6%minutes}. Stir in @diced tomatoes{1%can}
and @sugar{1/2%teaspoon}. Bring to a boil, then lower heat and let simmer until pasta is
done cooking. Stir in reserved pasta cooking water.

When eggplant is done, stir into pan with sauce, along with linguine, mozzarella, and
half the parsley. Toss until thoroughly combined and cheese has melted. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

Divide pasta mixture between plates and drizzle with @?olive oil{}, if desired. Garnish
with remaining parsley and serve.